   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="edition">
            <ab>
               <lb n="1"/>
               <persName>
                  <name key="Plato">Πλάτων</name>
                  <lb n="2"/>
                  <persName>
                     <name key="Ariston">Ἀρίστωνος</name>
                  </persName>
                  <lb n="3"/>Ἀθηναῖος</persName>
               <lb n="4"/>αἰτία· ἑλομέ
                    <lb n="5" break="no"/>νῳ θεὸς.
                    <lb n="6"/>ἀναίτιος
                    <lb/>
               <space quantity="4" unit="line"/>
               <lb n="7"/>ψυχὴ δὲ πᾶσα
                    <lb n="8"/>ἀθάνατος.
                </ab>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
           <p>Plato, son of Ariston, Athenian. Blame belongs to the one who chooses; god is blameless.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>The shaft of the herm is original but the inscription carved on it is a duplicate of a text inscribed on a similar herm first reported at Tivoli in 1846. That monument seems to have been inscribed sometime during the first century BCE and survives today at Tivoli in the palazzo municipale. The Berkeley herm inscribed in modern timnes with a duplicate text is first reported in 1901 as having been found 'near Rome' and was purchased (at a date not specified) from the antiquities dealers and brothers Ugo and Aldo Jandolo, who owned a gallery in Rome at 53 Via Margutta 198. Robert J. Smutney in 1966 untangled the object history of both herms, which were frequently confused in subsequent archaeological reports, correctly distinguishing the Berkeley stone from the Tivoli example on the basis of the missing head; traces of taeniae on the shoulders of the herm, which are incompatible with a bust of Plato; and discrepancies in the transcription of the Berkeley text, for which the carver seems to have copied not the original inscription but a misleading version of it transcribed by Stanislav Viola in 1848. Of the two allusions to Plato, each of which varies slightly from the original, the first, derived from Plato Republic 10.617E (αἰτία ἑλομένou, θεὸς ἀναίτιος), was frequently invoked by Roman authors of the early imperial period in discussions of free will. The second (with the addition of the particle δὲ) is taken from Plato, Phaedrus 245C (ψυχὴ πᾶσα ἀθάνατος). See further R. J. Smutney, Greek and Latin Inscriptons at Berkeley (Berkeley 1966)
Number 1, 2-5.</p>
         </div>
